### Server Components

React Server Components (RSC) run exclusively on the server at request time. They reduce the client bundle by keeping heavy dependencies and data fetching on the server.

---

### Key Characteristics

| Feature | Server Component | Client Component |
|---------|-----------------|-----------------|
| Execution | Server only | Browser + SSR |
| State/Effects | Not supported | Full support |
| Bundle size | Not sent to client | Included in JS bundle |
| Database access | Direct | Via API |
| File system access | Direct | Not accessible |

### Server Component Example

```jsx
// ProductList.server.js
import db from './database';

async function ProductList() {
  const products = await db.product.findMany();

  return (
    <ul>
      {products.map(product => (
        <li key={product.id}>
          {product.name} - ${product.price}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

### Client Component Directive

```jsx
'use client';

import { useState } from 'react';

export function AddToCart({ productId }) {
  const [added, setAdded] = useState(false);
  return (
    <button onClick={() => setAdded(true)}>
      {added ? 'Added!' : 'Add to Cart'}
    </button>
  );
}
```

### Composition Model

```jsx
// Server Component
import { AddToCart } from './AddToCart.client';

async function ProductPage({ id }) {
  const product = await db.product.findUnique(id);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{product.name}</h1>
      <p>{product.description}</p>
      <AddToCart productId={product.id} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

> **Key Point:** Server Components run once per request on the server. They cannot use hooks, event handlers, or browser APIs. Client Components are marked with `'use client'` and support interactivity. Next.js App Router uses RSCs by default.

